opological_sorting] order and any cycle in the reference graph will be broken.\n/tmp/specs2-5.5.0/guide/src/test/scala/org/specs2/guide/HtmlOutput.scala:15:If Markdown notation is used in the specification text and you have [Pandoc](http://johnmacfarlane.net/pandoc) installed on the command line\n/tmp/specs2-5.5.0/guide/src/test/scala/org/specs2/guide/HtmlOutput.scala:40:[Markdown](http://commonmark.org) text is supported if [Pandoc](http://johnmacfarlane.net/pandoc) is available on the command line and\n/tmp/specs2-5.5.0/guide/src/test/scala/org/specs2/guide/HtmlOutput.scala:49: `pandoc.inputformat`    | `markdown+pipe_tables+auto_identifiers+header_attributes+inline_code_attributes`  | pandoc arguments (see the Pandoc [user guide](http://johnmacfarlane.net/pandoc/README.html))\n/tmp/specs2-5.5.0/guide/src/test/scala/org/specs2/guide/UseScalaCheck.scala:24:A clever way of creating expectations in $specs2 is to use the [ScalaCheck](https://github.com/rickynils/scalacheck) library.\n/tmp/specs2-5.5.0/guide/src/test/scala/org/specs2/guide/UseScalaCheck.scala:146: `callback`        |                        | a ScalaCheck TestCallback (see the [ScalaCheck documentation](http://www.scalacheck.org))\n/tmp/specs2-5.5.0/guide/src/test/scala/org/specs2/guide/UseScalaCheck.scala:147: `loader`          |                        | a custom classloader (see the [ScalaCheck documentation](http://www.scalacheck.org))\n/tmp/specs2-5.5.0/guide/src/test/scala/org/specs2/guide/TroubleShooting.scala:13:The common symptom here is a `NullPointerException` for some attributes of your specification. You can refer to this [link](http://engineering.tapad.com/blog/2012/11/here-there-be-dragons-dangers-of-initialization-order-in-scala/) for an explanation of variable initialization in Scala. In the meantime the basic fix is to use a `lazy val` instead of a `val`.\n/tmp/specs2-5.5.0/guide/src/test/scala/org/specs2/guide/Matchers.scala:13:The most frequent way to specify some expected behaviour with $specs2 is to use _matchers_. You generally execute an action, a command or a function and then check if the actual value you get is equal to an expected one (the [\"arrange-act-assert\"](http://bit.ly/arrange_act_assert) paradigm).\n/tmp/specs2-5.5.0/guide/src/test/scala/org/specs2/guide/OtherBuildTools.scala:6:The most straightforward way to run $specs2 specifications is to use [sbt](http://scala-sbt.org).\n/tmp/specs2-5.5.0/guide/src/test/scala/org/specs2/guide/OtherBuildTools.scala:11:With Maven you need to use the [Surefire](http://maven.apache.org/surefire/maven-surefire-plugin/test-mojo.html) plugin and the `test` command.\n/tmp/specs2-5.5.0/guide/src/test/scala/org/specs2/guide/OtherBuildTools.scala:16:With Gradle the [`test`](http://www.gradle.org/docs/current/dsl/org.gradle.api.tasks.testing.Test.html) task will run your specification as a JUnit test suite.\n/tmp/specs2-5.5.0/guide/src/test/scala/org/specs2/guide/Specs2Variables.scala:12:  lazy val GUIDE_DIR = s\"https://etorreborre.github.io/specs2/guide/$VERSION\"\n/tmp/specs2-5.5.0/guide/src/test/scala/org/specs2/guide/Specs2Variables.scala:13:  lazy val SITE_DIR = s\"https://etorreborre.github.io/specs2/website/$VERSION\"\n/tmp/specs2-5.5.0/guide/src/test/scala/org/specs2/guide/Specs2Variables.scala:14:  lazy val API_DIR = s\"https://etorreborre.github.io/specs2/api/$VERSION\"\n/tmp/specs2-5.5.0/guide/src/test/scala/org/specs2/guide/Specs2Variables.scala:15:  lazy val PROJECT_DIR = s\"https://github.com/etorreborre/specs2/tree/$VERSION\"\n/tmp/specs2-5.5.0/guide/src/test/scala/org/specs2/guide/ExampleDescription.scala:9:[\"Don't repeat yourself\"](http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Don%27t_repeat_yourself) mandates that the same information is not repeated twice.\n/tmp/specs2-5.5.0/guide/src/test/scala/org/specs2/guide/Structure.scala:86:The first style encourages you to write [one expectation per example](http://bit.ly/one_assertion_per_test) while the second allows to use several.\n/tmp/specs2-5.5.0/gu